</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1398,764,826]" lastBlockId="7.[189,1399,267,480]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The present species corresponds to the morphospecies known as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Macquart, 1842)" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1842" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Tachytrechus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellatus">
<emphasis box="[973,1259,764,790]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Tachytrechus tessellatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Macquart J." pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="65 - 200" refId="ref6547" refString="Macquart J. 1842. Dipteres exotiques nouveaux ou peu connus. Memoires de la Societe des Sciences de l'Agriculture et des Arts de Lille 1841 (1): 65 - 200." type="journal article" year="1842">Macquart, 1842</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
described from 
<collectingCountry box="[464,561,799,825]" name="Senegal" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Senegal</collectingCountry>
. It has a wide Old World tropical and subtropical distribution from the 
<collectingCountry box="[235,373,267,293]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
archipelago in the west, all across continental Afrotropical Africa; in the Palaearctic realm it is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[475,540,304,330]" name="Israel" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Israel</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[601,674,305,331]" name="Egypt" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Egypt</collectingCountry>
, recorded throughout the 
<collectingRegion box="[982,1078,304,330]" country="Egypt" name="Ash Sharqiyah" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Oriental</collectingRegion>
Realm from the islands in the Indian Ocean, 
<collectingCountry box="[409,469,342,368]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[530,646,342,368]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[688,802,342,368]" name="Indonesia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry box="[907,1039,342,368]" name="Philippines" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Philippines</collectingCountry>
in the east (
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov I. Ya." box="[1188,1387,342,368]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref6456" refString="Grichanov I. Ya. 2018. An Annotated Catalogue of Aftrotropical Dolichopodoidae (Diptera). Plant Protection News Supplement 25. St Petersburg. https: // doi. org / 10.5281 / zenodo. 1187006" type="book" year="2018">Grichanov 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, we also recorded it from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[701,805,379,405]" name="Thailand" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[861,980,379,405]" name="Singapore" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Singapore</collectingCountry>
(Grootaert, Van de Velde &amp; Samoh, unpublished). There, it consists of two well separated populations with a barcode difference of 2.8% (Grootaert, Samoh &amp; Meier, unpublished).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3236101/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" startId="6.[189,232,1963,1989]" targetBox="[396,1169,877,1935]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1398,1963,2025]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,267,1963,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Macquart, 1842)" authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1842" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[275,775,1963,1989]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Tachytrechus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellatus">
<emphasis box="[275,559,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Tachytrechus tessellatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Macquart J." box="[575,767,1963,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="65 - 200" refId="ref6547" refString="Macquart J. 1842. Dipteres exotiques nouveaux ou peu connus. Memoires de la Societe des Sciences de l'Agriculture et des Arts de Lille 1841 (1): 65 - 200." type="journal article" year="1842">Macquart, 1842</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, male, habitus (leg. P. Grootaert and I. Van de Velde, RBINS; photo credit Rene Ong). Scale: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,521,622]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
We generally found this species along temporary bodies of water such as small lagoons on the supralittoral zone of the beach or in sun-exposed rainwater drains. On 
<collectingRegion box="[893,933,558,584]" country="Cape Verde" name="Sal" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Sal</collectingRegion>
, they were observed displaying on the border of an artificial water pit close to the beach.
</paragraph>
